  <p>The highlighted cell is our base case. Eaton's current share price of ${currentPrice.toFixed(2)} suggests the market is pricing the stock to perfection, anticipating significantly higher growth or a much lower required rate of return.</p>

  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Data Center Hyper-Growth:</strong> If AI-driven data center expansion accelerates beyond current forecasts, Eaton's power management and cooling solutions could see revenue and margin growth far exceeding our 12% FCF projection.</li>
    <li><strong>Grid Modernization Speed:</strong> Faster implementation of global energy transition initiatives (like the US Infrastructure Bill) could pull forward massive utility spending.</li>
    <li><strong>M&A Synergies:</strong> Eaton actively acquires smaller players. Accretive acquisitions not modeled here could boost long-term cash flows.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cyclical Downturn:</strong> Despite strong secular trends, Eaton remains exposed to broader industrial cycles. A significant macroeconomic recession could stall short-term growth.</li>
    <li><strong>Supply Chain Constraints:</strong> Ongoing shortages in critical electrical components could limit Eaton's ability to fulfill its record backlog, hampering near-term cash conversion.</li>
    <li><strong>Valuation Multiple Contraction:</strong> While DCF ignores multiples, the market does not. If growth slows even slightly, a stock priced for perfection could experience severe multiple compression regardless of cash flow generation.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use a 9% discount rate for Eaton?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Eaton is a mature, highly profitable industrial company with relatively predictable cash flows, which typically commands a lower risk premium than high-growth tech or volatile cyclical stocks. 9% offers a reasonable spread above the risk-free rate (4.18% 10Y Treasury) while acknowledging the company's stability.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is 12% FCF growth sustainable for an industrial company?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Historically, no. However, Eaton is currently riding unprecedented secular tailwinds in electrification, grid modernization, and AI data center buildouts. This unique convergence of demand drivers makes a 12% growth rate plausible for a 5-year phase, before reverting to a normal terminal rate.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why does the model say the stock is overvalued?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">A DCF calculates what the cash flows are worth. If the market price is higher than the intrinsic value, it means the market expects either faster growth, longer growth duration, or accepts a lower rate of return than our model assumes. Eaton's current price reflects extreme market optimism regarding its role in the AI and electrification megatrends.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How does the net debt impact the valuation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Eaton carries roughly $10.5 billion in total debt against roughly $800 million in cash and short-term investments. This net debt of ~$9.7 billion is subtracted from the Enterprise Value. While the debt is manageable, it directly reduces the final Equity Value available to shareholders.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

